Questions:

Which Machine Learning Methods did you Implement?

I implemented PCA with an unsupervised learning technique of hierarchical clustering to better understand the landscape of the data since I believe there to be a hierarchical structure to the data. The next model I used was a lasso regression, which was chosen due to its high performance, interpretability, and ability to automatically reduce dimensionality, as we have many predictors available. Next, I use XGBoost boosted tree model, which allows for the production of feature importance charts and PDP plots while also regularizing the data to prevent overfitting. Finally, I employed a softmax neural network, which is well-suited for handling complex, non-linear relationships between features and the target variable. This models ability to handle multiple independent variables without extensive feature engineering makes it a valuable tool for our analysis.

Discuss the key contribution of each method to your analysis.

Each model contributed new information to our analysis. The PCA and hierarchical clustering in the data seemed to show that there were clear hierarchical relationships among many of the clusters in the data. After clustering the data, we observed distinct differences between the clusters in terms of compensation levels, software development experience, and academic affiliations.

Next, the lasso regression contributed a very detailed view into the coefficient and odds ratios for what the algorithm deemed to be the most impactful predictors. Because of its efficiency, the lasso regression also allowed for us to view some of the specific languages and their relationship with wanting to learn R through the coefficent chart. The XGBoost models PDP and feature importance charts also offered key insights into the relationships between the target and predictor variables, confirming many of the observations from the lasso regression. Finally, the neural network, while not able to outperform the XGBoost or lasso regression model, was fit to a much smaller dataset that underwent 42 different combinations hyperparameters in its 5-level and 5-fold cross validation, and still performed well on the training data. This indicates that even if the other two models performed better on the metrics of F1 and accuracy with the test data, the neural network model could become useful if the other two predictive methods show signs of overfitting in real-world application.

Did all methods support your conclusions or did some provide conflicting results

While the PCA and hierarchical clustering provided a general overview of the data, initial observations revealed that the cluster with the least interest in R also had the highest average compensation, a relatively young demographic, and a significant presence in the software development industry. These findings would be backed by the lasso regression, which also showed that younger populations, those in the software industry, and those with higher compensations had negative relationships with wanting to learn R. The XGBoost model, through its PDP charts, also showed the same relationship for compensation.

For the two predictive models that produced interpretable outputs, we can see that both models seemed to agree that interest in other data-related languages such as SQL, Python, and others displayed a positive relationship with the target variable of to wanting to work with R. However, the XGBoost model presented a contrasting finding to the Lasso regression and clustering results. The XGBoost model suggested a slight positive relationship between age and interest in R, indicating that younger audiences might be more inclined to learn R. Also, the XGBoost model showed Industry_Energy to be one of the more valuable predictors, whereas the lasso regression seemed to eliminate it during its feature reduction step. However, both models indicated a positive correlation between interest in scripting languages and interest in R. Generally, when models yielded conflicting results, I evaluated the context of each model, considering factors such as sensitivity to noise and alignment with theoretical expectations. Additionally, I assessed whether the findings of one model were supported by other models in the analysis. In the end, all of the models showed comparable performance metrics and each offered an unique advantage to predicting whether a developer may want to work with R in the future.

Data Cleaning and Preparation

First, before running our models, we clean the data through one-hot encoding, grouping together categorical variables of interest, and scaling our numerical variables while eliminating outliers.

One-Hot Encoding

Our first step in this process is to one-hot encode some of our variables and group some of our variables together into categories for ease of analysis. We also handle nas in these variables by adding them to their own missing category.

#this function searches for semi-colons in the data and seperates the values
# between them in order to create unqiue binary columns for interest in specific languages
OneHotEncodeFactor <- function(variable, data, prefix){

data_sep <- separate_rows(data, variable, sep = ";")

one_hot_encoded <- data_sep %>%
  mutate(Value = 1) %>%
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = variable,
    names_prefix = prefix,
    values_from = Value,
    values_fill = list(Value = 0)
  )
return(one_hot_encoded)
}
# select specific columns from raw data
one_hot_data <- rawData[, c('ResponseId','LanguageHaveWorkedWith', 'LanguageWantToWorkWith', 'Industry', 'Age', 'Country','EdLevel', 'YearsCode', 'YearsCodePro', 'WorkExp', 'CompTotal', 'DevType', 'AISelect')]
# oe-hot encode language related features
one_hot_data <- OneHotEncodeFactor('LanguageHaveWorkedWith', one_hot_data, "have_worked_with")
one_hot_data <- OneHotEncodeFactor('LanguageWantToWorkWith', one_hot_data, "want_to_work_with")

# impute missing values in Industry with "Missing" category
one_hot_data$Industry[is.na(one_hot_data$Industry)] <- "Missing"

# Create dummy variables for Industry (including the first category)
one_hot_data <- dummy_cols(one_hot_data, select_columns = "Industry", remove_first_dummy = FALSE)

# Create binary feature for younger age groups
one_hot_data <- one_hot_data %>%
  mutate(is_younger = ifelse(Age %in% c("18-24 years old", "25-34 years old"), 1, 0))

# Filter data for US respondents only
one_hot_data <- one_hot_data %>%
  filter(Country == "United States of America")

# Create binary features for education levels
one_hot_data <- one_hot_data %>%
  mutate(advanced_ed = ifelse(EdLevel %in% c("Masters degree (M.A., M.S., M.Eng., MBA, etc.)", "Professional degree (JD, MD, Ph.D, Ed.D, etc.)"), 1, 0))

one_hot_data <- one_hot_data %>%
  mutate(higher_ed = ifelse(EdLevel %in% c("Bachelors degree (B.A., B.S., B.Eng., etc.)", "Associate degree (A.A., A.S., etc.)"), 1, 0))

one_hot_data <- one_hot_data %>%
  mutate(lower_than_higher_ed = ifelse(EdLevel %in% c("Primary/elementary school", "Secondary school (e.g. American high school, German Realschule or Gymnasium, etc.)", "Some college/university study without earning a degree"), 1, 0))

# Convert numeric features to numeric data type
one_hot_data$YearsCode <- as.numeric(one_hot_data$YearsCode)
one_hot_data$YearsCodePro <- as.numeric(one_hot_data$YearsCodePro)
one_hot_data$CompTotal <- as.numeric(one_hot_data$CompTotal)
one_hot_data$WorkExp <- as.numeric(one_hot_data$WorkExp)

# Create binary feature for academic professions
one_hot_data <- one_hot_data %>%
  mutate(academic_prof = ifelse(DevType %in% c("Academic researcher", "Scientist", 
                                               "Student"), 1, 0))
# Create binary feature for intention to use AI
one_hot_data <- one_hot_data %>%
  mutate(use_AI = ifelse(AISelect %in% c("Yes", "No, but I plan to soon"), 1, 0))

# Create binary feature for having worked with R
one_hot_data <- one_hot_data %>%
  mutate(have_worked_withR = ifelse(have_worked_withR == 1, 1, 0))

# Create binary feature for wanting to work with R
one_hot_data <- one_hot_data %>%
  mutate(want_to_work_withR = ifelse(want_to_work_withR == 1, 1, 0))

Numerical Data Cleanig

Next, we clean our numerical values through median imputation for nulls.

#rid of extra columns
stg_data <- one_hot_data[, !names(one_hot_data) %in% c("Age", "Industry", "Country", "EdLevel", "DevType", "AISelect")]
#median impute nulls for numerical variables
stg_data <- stg_data %>%
  mutate(
    CompTotal = ifelse(is.na(CompTotal), median(CompTotal, na.rm = TRUE), CompTotal),
    YearsCode = ifelse(is.na(YearsCode), median(YearsCode, na.rm = TRUE), YearsCode),
    YearsCodePro = ifelse(is.na(YearsCodePro), median(YearsCodePro, na.rm = TRUE), YearsCodePro),
    WorkExp = ifelse(is.na(WorkExp), median(WorkExp, na.rm = TRUE), WorkExp)
  )

Unsupervised Clustering with PCA

The first step of our analysis will be to investigate the overall landscape of the data through hierarchical clustering. Hierarchical clustering was chosen due to its ability to determine the optimal number of clusters by itself and since we suspect that there may be a hierarchical relationship in our data (for an example, you may see a split for more experienced developers that then branches into those who work with data science, full stack developers, etc.)

PCA

Before clustering, we will first transform our data into its principle components. This will reduce the dimenisonality of our data and hopefully speed up the process of analysis while focusing on the components that capture the most variance in our data.

set.seed(123)

#Calculate variance-covariance mix
cov_w <- cov(justnumsData)

#get eigenvalues and eigen vectors
e_w <- eigen(cov_w)
eigenval <- e_w$values

#estimate percent of variance explained
var_exp <- round(eigenval/sum(eigenval),3)
#get cumulative variance explained by each component

From the output, we can see that the correlation between the variables is minimal. Now lets move onto our linkage methods to finishing our clustering analysis.

Trying different linkage methods

Now that we have our packages for clustering, we will try 2 different hierarchical clustering methods: Ward and Complete. We are using a hierarchical clustering algorithm as it allows for us to create clusters when we are uncertain on the amount required.

#get pca distances using euclidean distance
d <- dist(pca_w, method = "euclidean")
#use ward method for dendrogram
fit.w <- hclust(d,method="ward.D2")
#plot dendrogram for ward linkage
plot(fit.w, main = "Ward Linkage", xlab = "Observations", ylab = "Height", cex = .6)

It looks like we have many clusters here, but can observe the main cutoffs seem to occur around ~50. Lets try an average linkage to see if that produces better results:

set.seed(123)
#use ward method for dendrogram
fit.a <- hclust(d,method="average")
#plot dendrogram for average linkage
plot(fit.a, main = "Average Linkage", xlab = "Observations", ylab = "Height", cex = .6)

From the average linkage, we can see that the main split seems to occur around a height of 9, with a small group of likely outliers separated from a larger division of splits. We will now proceed to our final dendrogram utilizing the complete linkage method.

set.seed(123)
#use complete method for dendrogram
fit.c <- hclust(d,method="complete")
#plot complete dendrogram
plot(fit.c, main = "Complete Linkage", xlab = "Observations", ylab = "Height", cex = .6)

The chart still looks pretty messy, but there are still clear splits in the data. Lets check our cophenetic correlation coefficients to see which of the linkage methods performs best.

set.seed(123)
d.coph <- cophenetic(fit.w) # ward linkage
cat('Wards Linkage', cor(d, d.coph))
## Wards Linkage 0.4321144
d.coph <- cophenetic(fit.a) # average linkage
cat('\nAverage Linkage', cor(d, d.coph))
## 
## Average Linkage 0.7395169
d.coph <- cophenetic(fit.c) # complete linkage
cat('\nComplete Linkage', cor(d, d.coph))
## 
## Complete Linkage 0.6753164

Of the three linkage methods, the average linkage method seemed to produce the highest cophenetic correlation coefficient at 0.739. However, it also seemed to have the produce branches that seemed influenced the most by outliers in the data due to the small branch at the top of the data. Complete linkage method, however, is more robust to outliers compared to the average method. As we are looking to gather an overall view of the data, we will proceed with using the complete method instead.

Lasso Regression

The first predictive model chosen was a Lasso regression. A lasso regression suits our data well as it is able to reduce the dimensionality of the data to the most impactful variables and is not computationally intensive.

Setup Train and Test

The first step in our process is to set up a train and test split, for which we assign 80% of our data to train and 20% to test. After doing so, we then use SMOTE to oversample our minority class to prevent bias from class imbalance.

set.seed(123)

#get index to divide data into training and test sets
index <- createDataPartition(final_Data$want_to_work_withR, p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
#create training and test sets
train_data <- final_Data[index,]
test_data <- final_Data[-index,]
#ensure variables are numeric
train_data[] <- lapply(train_data, as.numeric)
#factor target variable
train_data$want_to_work_withR <- as.factor(train_data$want_to_work_withR)

Fit Lasso Model

Next, to fit our lasso model we use cross validation with an MSE measure to determine the best level of lambda for our model.

set.seed(123)
#get our x and y variables assigned
x <- data.matrix(train_data[, !names(final_Data) %in% c("ResponseId" ,"want_to_work_withR")])
y <- train_data$want_to_work_withR
#fit lasso model to get best lambda in 5 fold cv
cv.lasso <- cv.glmnet(x, y, alpha = 1, nfolds = 5, type.measure = "mse", standardize=TRUE,family='binomial')
#plot the model 
plot(cv.lasso)

The Lasso plot allows us to see that the mean squared error and log(lambda) stay constant until around ~-4, then beings to increase. From this, it looks like the optimal lambda value would be around -2.

Testing the Linear Model

Before we argue for the significance of these coefficents, lets first check the performance of the model on the test data to see if it can accurately predict whether a user will be interested in R.

set.seed(123)
#get x and y variables from test data
X_test <- as.matrix(test_data[, -which(names(test_data) %in% c("want_to_work_withR", "ResponseId"))])
y_test <- test_data$want_to_work_withR
#get predicted values using our model
predictions <- predict(cv.lasso, s = "lambda.min", newx = X_test, type = "response")
# Convert the probabilities to binary outcomes (threshold at 0.5)
predicted_classes <- ifelse(predictions > 0.5, 1, 0)

# Evaluate performance: Accuracy
accuracy <- mean(predicted_classes == y_test)
print(paste("Accuracy:", accuracy))
## [1] "Accuracy: 0.965237020316027"
# Confusion Matrix
confusionMatrix <- confusionMatrix(data = factor(predicted_classes), reference = factor(y_test))
print(confusionMatrix$table)
##           Reference
## Prediction    0    1
##          0 2112   58
##          1   19   26
accuracy <- confusionMatrix$overall['Accuracy']
precision <- confusionMatrix$byClass['Precision']
recall <- confusionMatrix$byClass['Sensitivity']
f1_score <- 2 * (precision * recall) / (precision + recall)

# Calculate AUC-ROC
roc_curve <- roc(y_test, predictions)
auc_value <- auc(roc_curve)
print(paste("AUC-ROC:", auc_value))
## [1] "AUC-ROC: 0.861676275390494"
# Plot ROC curve
plot(roc_curve, main = "ROC Curve", col = "blue")

print(paste("Accuracy:", round(accuracy,4)))
## [1] "Accuracy: 0.9652"
print(paste("Precision:", round(precision,4)))
## [1] "Precision: 0.9733"
print(paste("Recall:", round(recall,4)))
## [1] "Recall: 0.9911"
print(paste("F1-Score:", round(f1_score,4))) 
## [1] "F1-Score: 0.9821"

From our model, we can see our accuracy is high (96%), with the confusion matrix doing a pretty solid job of identifying true and false positives. The F1 score is also very high, showing that the model s able to balance percision and recall well. AUC-ROC also backs these findings by showing the ability of the model to distinguish between the classes. The 0.86 score is good, meaning the model is doing a decent job of ranking positive instances higher than negative ones and we can see the ROC hug the upper right of the chart, which is ideal.

Now that we have prepped our data for the XGBoost model, we can fit our models through cross validation utilizing a grid search to chose the optimal hyperparameters to maximize performance on F-measure.

Recipe for Ensemble Method

set.seed(123)
rec_wantR <- recipe(want_to_work_withR~., SmoteTrainData) #train model using smote data using churn as target and all other variables as predictors
#define model
model_wantR <- boost_tree( #use boosted tree
  trees = tune(), #tune number of trees through grid search
  tree_depth = tune(), #tune tree_depth through grid search
  learn_rate = tune()) %>% #tune learning rate through grid search
    set_engine('xgboost', verbosity = 1) %>% #use xgboost as engine
    set_mode("classification") #model type set to classification
#specify hyperparameter gird to do 2 level grid search through the 3 hyperparameters
hyper_grid <- grid_regular(
  trees(), tree_depth(), learn_rate(), levels=2
)
#Set 5 fold cross validation
want_R_folds <- vfold_cv(SmoteTrainData, v=5)

#Define workflow for the model by adding the recipe and the model to the workflow object
wantR_wf <- workflow() %>%
  add_model(model_wantR) %>%
  add_recipe(rec_wantR)

#set up computer to use parallelism to increase performance
doParallel::registerDoParallel(cores=4)
# set seed for replication

#Start runing through cross validation and model fitting to get best hyperparameters
wantR_tune <- wantR_wf %>% 
  tune_grid(
  resamples = want_R_folds,
  grid=hyper_grid,
  metrics = metric_set(f_meas) #return f-measure each iteration 
  )


#get all the metrics from the iterations
best_metric <- collect_metrics(wantR_tune)

# Select the best hyperparameters to use 
best_index <- which.max(best_metric$mean)
best_params <- best_metric[best_index, ]

# Finalize the workflow with the best parameters
final_wf <- finalize_workflow(wantR_wf, best_params)

# Fit the final model to the training data
final_fit <- fit(final_wf, data = SmoteTrainData)

#make predictions 
predictions <- predict(final_fit, new_data = test_data)
#create confusion matrix
confusionMatrix <- confusionMatrix(as.factor(test_data$want_to_work_withR), predictions$.pred_class)
#get accuracy, percision, recall, and F1 score from confusion matrix for our optimal model
accuracy <- confusionMatrix$overall['Accuracy']
precision <- confusionMatrix$byClass['Precision']
recall <- confusionMatrix$byClass['Sensitivity']
f1_score <- 2 * (precision * recall) / (precision + recall)
#Output performance metrics
print(paste("Accuracy:", accuracy))
## [1] "Accuracy: 0.947202166064982"
print(paste("Precision:", precision))
## [1] "Precision: 0.967544684854186"
print(paste("Recall:", recall))
## [1] "Recall: 0.977197149643705"
print(paste("F1-Score:", f1_score)) 
## [1] "F1-Score: 0.972346962892933"
print(confusionMatrix)

Neural Net (SoftMax) Model

The final model we will run is the neural net model utilizing softmax. This model was chosen due to its ability to model non-linear relationships and handle multi-dimensional data well. It is the goal of this model to produce a high performing model that can be used for predictive power, as we will not be able to interpret the output of the neural network due to it being a blackbox algorithim.

Formulating the Neural Net

In our neural net, we will only use a small subsample of the data of 500 observations. While this was primarily chosen due to performance concerns, it could also help lower the chances of overfitting. Additionally in our neural nets setup, we set up a 5-fold cross validation that repeats 5 times to try 20 different values of size and 2 different values of decay in order for the model to select the hyperparamets that improve the accuracy of the model the most.

library(caret)
library(mlbench)
library(doParallel)
library(dplyr)
library(performanceEstimation)
library(rsample)
registerDoParallel(cores = 4 )

set.seed(123)
#get index to divide data into training and test sets
index <- createDataPartition(BaggingData_copy$want_to_work_withR, p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
#create training and test sets
train_data <- BaggingData_copy[index,]
test_data <- BaggingData_copy[-index,]
#esnrue data is numeric
train_data[] <- lapply(train_data, as.numeric)

#sample 500 observations from the data randomly
sample_indices <- sample(1:nrow(train_data), 500)
Sampled_train_data <- train_data[sample_indices,]

#factor target variable into character values to work with the neural net's function
test_data$want_to_work_withR <- as.factor(ifelse(test_data$want_to_work_withR == 1, "Yes", "No"))
Sampled_train_data$want_to_work_withR <- as.factor(ifelse(Sampled_train_data$want_to_work_withR == 1, "Yes", "No"))
#display before and after SMOTE class balance
print("Before SMOTE")
## [1] "Before SMOTE"
print(table(Sampled_train_data$want_to_work_withR))
## 
##  No Yes 
## 476  24
#balance classes using SMOTE
SmoteTrainData <- smote(want_to_work_withR ~ ., data = Sampled_train_data, perc.under = 1, perc.over = 20)
print("After SMOTE")
## [1] "After SMOTE"
print(table(SmoteTrainData$want_to_work_withR))
## 
##  No Yes 
## 480 504
#Get prediction and outcome for training and test datasets
#...for train
SmoteTrainData_Pred <- SmoteTrainData[, !names(SmoteTrainData) %in% c('want_to_work_withR')]
SmoteTrainData_Outcome <- SmoteTrainData$want_to_work_withR
#...and for test
test_pred <- test_data[, !names(test_data) %in% c('want_to_work_withR')]
test_pred[] <- lapply(test_pred, as.numeric)
test_outcome <- test_data$want_to_work_withR

#set up cross validation
crtl <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv",
                     number = 5, #do 5-fold cv
                     repeats = 5,
                     classProbs = TRUE) #report class probabilities

#this will have the model try 42 different models and chose the optimal value from them 
NNGrid <- expand.grid(decay = c(0.001, 0.005),
                      size = c(15:35),
                      bag = FALSE)
#Ensure column names can work with the algorithm
names(test_pred) <- make.names(names(test_pred))
names(SmoteTrainData_Pred) <- make.names(names(SmoteTrainData_Pred))

#Train the model using our smote'd data
NN_fit <- train(SmoteTrainData_Pred, SmoteTrainData_Outcome,
                method = "avNNet", #use avnnet to prevent overfitting
                tuneGrid = NNGrid, # use grid set up earlier
                trControl = crtl, # and cross validation
                softmax = TRUE, #softmax for classification task
                #preProc = c("center", "scale"),
                trace = FALSE, 
                metric = "Accuracy", #get accuracy of model
                allowParallel = TRUE, #use parallelism to improve performance
                maxit = 20) #20 iterations

Predicted Outcomes and Performance Metrics

Now that our model has run, we can see how the precited outcomes compare to the actual data from our test data.

set.seed(123)
plot(NN_fit)

#get predicted outcome values
predicted_outcomes <- predict(NN_fit, test_pred)
postResample(pred= factor(predicted_outcomes), obs = factor(test_outcome))
##  Accuracy     Kappa 
## 0.9282167 0.2706498
#Output confusion  matrix
confusionMatrix <- confusionMatrix(data = factor(predicted_outcomes), reference = factor(test_outcome))
print(confusionMatrix$table)
##           Reference
## Prediction   No  Yes
##        No  2021   49
##        Yes  110   35
#Get accuracy, F1 Score and other performance metrics
accuracy <- confusionMatrix$overall['Accuracy']
precision <- confusionMatrix$byClass['Precision']
recall <- confusionMatrix$byClass['Sensitivity']
f1_score <- 2 * (precision * recall) / (precision + recall)

print(paste("Accuracy:", round(accuracy,4)))
## [1] "Accuracy: 0.9282"
print(paste("Precision:", round(precision,4)))
## [1] "Precision: 0.9763"
print(paste("Recall:", round(recall,4)))
## [1] "Recall: 0.9484"
print(paste("F1-Score:", round(f1_score,4))) 
## [1] "F1-Score: 0.9622"

From the charts output, we can see that the model with 19 hidden units and a weight decay of 0.001 performed the best. Once compared to the test data, we can see that the model had an accuracy of 0.9282 and an F1-score of 0.9622. While these results are still high performing, it does not out-compete the other two models, which also offered the benefits of being more interpretable and less computationally intensive. It is for this reason that the neural net will likely not be our model of choice to predict whether a developer would be interested in R.
